<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/2569931-shannon"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1425744028i/2569931._UX100_CR0,16,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/2569931-shannon">Shannon</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Princess Bride is the only time that I would say that the book and the movie are just as good as each other. It helps that the same person wrote both <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Princess Bride is the only time that I would say that the book and the movie are just as good as each other. It helps that the same person wrote both the book and the screenplay. If you love the movie you'll love the book too; nothing is really changed, it just has more detail, more background, more events. They're both amazing and, for once, it's possible to love both the book AND the movie. :)<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
